Crack, Clarity... whatevah.  A friend of mine regularly plays on my LAN on his account over at my place, and I often pair my Enchanter up with his Monk.  They make a great pair.  When his haste spell flavor-of-the-month is fading, he'll often pipe up and say something like, "Ack, melee crack fading."  Should I glare at him coldly and state that "I don't deal in crack, Dylan?".  Pssh.  I understood what he meant and I know that he didn't mean any offense by it (nor am I able to see how any could be taken).<P>Melees are frequently called meatshields, and yet they neither resemble a slab of meat (except for ogres) nor do they resemble shields.  A wizard is commonly called a nuker, yet I haven't seen one that possessed a thermonuclear weapon..  A cleric is called a healer... but that's not all they can do.<P>o_O<P>Should any of these classes get angry about it?  Sheesh.  I remember when the term "crack" first started getting used... back when if you said, "crack plz" to an Enchanter, they'd look at you oddly and wonder what the heck you meant.  "Crack" was and to some extent still is an endearing term... a compliment to Enchanters that their spells are so unbelievably addictive to have that they could be compared to a potent narcotic substance.<P>Granted, the term has lost some of it's charm over time... much like "Who Let The Dogs Out", Vanilla Ice, or "All Your Base Are Belong To Us"... but dangit, it had good intentions to begin with.   <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"><P>I do agree with Iliadari though.  Enchanters aren't there to simply deal out "da crack" on demand... much less are we obligated to do so even if offered compensation.
